The Russian news service TASS and several other state-owned media companies have been taken down by the Anonymous hacker collective. In its latest move against Vladimir Putin, the hacker groups have disabled news services and replaced their websites with anti-war messages. The messages are described as a ‘tombstone’ for the war dead. Russian media networks Kommersant, Izvestia, Fontaka, RBC have also been attacked by Anonymous. For the latest updates on the Russia-Ukraine war, visit our live blog:  Russia-Ukraine live It is the latest high profile cyber attack made as part of the fight against Russia’s invasion of Ukraine. One of the messages displayed on the hacked sites include the number ‘5,300’, the number of Russian troops that Ukraine claims to have killed. The Anonymous statement also suggest Putin has begun the invasion to ‘get into the history books’. The message includes a plea to the Russian people: ‘We urge you to stop this madness, do not send your sons and husbands to certain death.’ Founded in 1904, TASS is Russia’s leading news agencies. Controlled by Vladimir Putin, it is a state-run media network responsible for newspapers, websites, radio and TV stations. MORE : Anonymous sends blunt message to Vladimir Putin over invasion of Ukraine MORE : Anonymous ‘hacks Russian TV to show footage from Ukraine front lines’